To make the `OnMouseEnter()` function work on a 2D sprite in Unity, follow these steps:

1. Create a new script to attach to the object that has the sprite. Right-click in the Project window -> Create -> C# script and name it "MouseEnterScript".

2. Attach the newly created script to the object containing the sprite. Select the object in the Scene or Hierarchy window, then drag and drop the script onto the object or use the Add Component button in the Inspector window.

3. Open the "MouseEnterScript" script by double-clicking on it in the Project window, which will open it in your default script editor.

4. Remove the `Start()` and `Update()` functions from the script, as they are not needed for this purpose.

5. Add the `OnMouseEnter()` function below the `Monobehaviour` class declaration. This function gets called whenever the mouse cursor enters the collider of the sprite.

   ```csharp
   using UnityEngine;

   public class MouseEnterScript : MonoBehaviour
   {
       private void OnMouseEnter()
       {
           // Code to execute when the mouse cursor enters the sprite's collider
           Debug.Log("Mouse entered!");
       }
   }
   ```

6. Save the script (Ctrl + S or Command + S).

7. Make sure that the object's sprite has a `BoxCollider2D` component attached to the object. If it doesn't have one, add it by selecting the object and then clicking on Add Component -> Physics2D -> Box Collider 2D in the Inspector window.

8. Finally, play the Unity scene by pressing the Play button at the top of the Unity Editor window, and move the mouse cursor over the sprite. The `OnMouseEnter()` function will be called, and the "Mouse entered!" message will be displayed in the Unity Console window.

That's it! You have successfully implemented the `OnMouseEnter()` function on a 2D sprite in Unity.

If you want to call the `OnMouseButtonDrag()` function in Unity only when hovering over a new 2D object rather than every frame, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a new script and attach it to the object that you want to detect the drag on. Right-click in the Project window -> Create -> C# script and name it "MouseDragScript".

2. Attach the newly created script to the object. Select the object in the Scene or Hierarchy window, then drag and drop the script onto the object or use the Add Component button in the Inspector window.

3. Open the "MouseDragScript" script in your default script editor.

4. Add the necessary using directive for Unity's 2D physics library by inserting the following line at the top of the script:

   ```csharp
   using UnityEngine;
   ```

5. Remove the existing `Start()` and `Update()` functions from the script, as you don't need them for this purpose.

6. Declare a boolean variable to keep track of whether the mouse is currently hovering over an object. Add the following line below the class declaration:

   ```csharp
   private bool isHovering = false;
   ```

7. Add the `OnMouseEnter()` function below the `Monobehaviour` class declaration. This function gets called when the mouse cursor enters the collider of the 2D object.

   ```csharp
   private void OnMouseEnter()
   {
       isHovering = true;
   }
   ```

8. Add the `OnMouseExit()` function below the `OnMouseEnter()` function. This function gets called when the mouse cursor exits the collider of the 2D object.

   ```csharp
   private void OnMouseExit()
   {
       isHovering = false;
   }
   ```

9. Finally, add the `OnMouseDrag()` function below the `OnMouseExit()` function. This function gets called when the mouse cursor is dragged while the left mouse button is held down.

   ```csharp
   private void OnMouseDrag()
   {
       if (isHovering)
       {
           // Code to execute when the left mouse button is dragged over the object
           Debug.Log("Mouse dragged!");
       }
   }
   ```

10. Save the script (Ctrl + S or Command + S).

11. Make sure that the object's sprite has a `BoxCollider2D` component attached to it. If it doesn't have one, add it by selecting the object and then clicking on Add Component -> Physics2D -> Box Collider 2D in the Inspector window.

Now, whenever you hover over a new 2D object with the mouse cursor and drag the left mouse button, the `OnMouseDrag()` function will be called only for the newly hovered object.

