   ```

3. Update the `GenerateGrid()` method to assign the instantiated circles to the `circles` array:

   ```csharp
   private void GenerateGrid()
   {
       circles = new GameObject[gridSizeX, gridSizeY];

       for (int x = 0; x < gridSizeX; x++)
       {
           for (int y = 0; y < gridSizeY; y++)
           {
               Vector2 position = new Vector2(x * spacing, y * spacing);
               gridPositions[x, y] = position;
               GameObject circle = InstantiateCircle(position);
               circles[x, y] = circle;
           }
       }
   }
   ```

4. Add a new method called `MoveTilesDown()` to move the tiles downwards in the grid:

   ```csharp
   private void MoveTilesDown()
   {
       for (int x = 0; x < gridSizeX; x++)
       {
           for (int y = 1; y < gridSizeY; y++)
           {
               if (circles[x, y] == null && circles[x, y - 1] != null)
               {
                   circles[x, y - 1].transform.position += new Vector3(0f, -spacing, 0f);
                   circles[x, y] = circles[x, y - 1];
                   circles[x, y - 1] = null;
               }
           }
       }
   }
   ```

   This method iterates through each column in the grid, starting from the second row. If the current position is empty (`circles[x, y] == null`) and the position above it is not empty (`circles[x, y - 1] != null`), it moves the tile downwards by adjusting its position and updates the `circles` array accordingly.

5. Modify the `OnMouseUp()` function to call the `MoveTilesDown()` method:

   ```csharp
   private void OnMouseUp()
   {
       MoveTilesDown();
   }
   ```

6. Save the script.

Now, when the mouse button is released, the `MoveTilesDown()` method will be called. If there is an empty spot beneath a tile, the tile will move downwards, filling the empty spot in the grid.

